Proceeding as in the hints, recall that $R = pq$ and thus

\begin{align*}\frac{dR}{dt} = q\frac{dp}{dt} + p\frac{dq}{dt}\end{align*}

Plugging in $\frac{dR}{dt} = 0.15$ and $p=4$ and $q=2$ gives

\begin{align*}0.15 = 2\frac{dp}{dt} + 4\frac{dq}{dt}\end{align*}

Notice that we have two unknowns and one equation so we'll need to find
another equation to get our target value of $\frac{dp}{dt}$. This means
we need to eliminate $\frac{dq}{dt}$. To do this we can differentiate
the original demand equation given in the problem with respect to t,

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(q^2+p^{3/2}+2p\right)&=\frac{d}{dt}20\\
2q\frac{dq}{dt} + \frac{3\sqrt{p}}{2} \frac{dp}{dt} + 2\frac{dp}{dt}&= 0.\end{align*}

Plugging in the information above gives

\begin{align*}2(2)\frac{dq}{dt} + \frac{3\sqrt{4}}{2} \frac{dp}{dt} + 2\frac{dp}{dt} = 0\end{align*}

and simplifying

\begin{align*}4\frac{dq}{dt} + 5\frac{dp}{dt} = 0\end{align*}

This gives us our second equation. Subtracting the second equation from
the first gives

\begin{align*}3\frac{dp}{dt} = -0.15\end{align*}

and thus

\begin{align*}\frac{dp}{dt} = -0.05\end{align*}

So the rate in price must be changed by a decrease of 5 cents (0.05
dollars) per hour completing the question.
